You can use `html-webpack-plugin`

You can define any variables in your `webpack.config.js` including html:

    new HtmlWebpackPlugin({
        template: &#39;./src/index.html&#39;,
        header: &#39;&lt;h1&gt;A title&lt;/h1&gt;&#39;,
        anyElement: &#39;&lt;b&gt;I am an html element&lt;/b&gt;&#39;
    })

Then you can insert them into your `index.html` like this:

    &lt;html&gt;
        &lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;
        &lt;body&gt;
            &lt;%= htmlWebpackPlugin.options.header %&gt;
            &lt;h1&gt;Some Other Html Content&lt;/h1&gt;
            &lt;%= htmlWebpackPlugin.options.footer %&gt;
        &lt;/body&gt;
    &lt;/html&gt;


If you have external html files that you want to use you can do that by using the node js integrated module called `fs` to read the files and then pass the into your variables. You don&#39;t need to install `fs` as it comes with nodejs

    let fs = require(&#39;fs&#39;);

    const myFile = fs.readFileSync(__dirname + &#39;/myfile.html&#39;);
    const thatFile = fs.readFileSync(__dirname + &#39;/thatfile.html&#39;);

    module.exports = {

        // your config

        plugins: [
          new HtmlWebpackPlugin({
            template: &#39;./src/index.html&#39;,
            myFile: myFile,
            thatFile: thatFile,
          })
         ]
    });

Now when you run Webpack your HTML file will be injected in the places you have specified.


    &lt;html&gt;
        &lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;
        &lt;body&gt;
            &lt;%= htmlWebpackPlugin.options.myFile %&gt;
            &lt;h1&gt;Some other html content&lt;/h1&gt;
            &lt;%= htmlWebpackPlugin.options.yourFile %&gt;
        &lt;/body&gt;
    &lt;/html&gt;

